<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06337041 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06337041 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  JAPAN; WORLD; WAR; HISTORY; AIR; ASSAULT; DATE; CEREMONY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The lower house of parliament is considering marking the 50th anniversary ofJapan's attack on Pearl Harbor with an apology to the United States, publishedreports said Sunday.;   But in Washington, President Bush, in a tapedinterview broadcast Sunday, rejected any suggestion that the United Statesowes Japan an apology for dropping atomic bombs on Hiroshima and Nagasaki in1945, saying the bombings may have saved millions of American lives.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  JAPAN WEIGHS APOLOGY FOR PEARL HARBORNO SIMILAR GESTURE ON A-BOMBS, BUSH SAYS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  50 YEARS AGO: A look back through the eyes of our readers. Page 1D  </MEMO><TEXT>     Japanese lawmakers plan to adopt the resolution to mark the 50thanniversary of the Dec. 7 attack, Kyodo News Service said in a report, quotingunidentified sources close to the governing Liberal Democratic Party.;   Morethan 2,300 people died and 19 warships were sunk in the Sunday morning attackon the Pearl Harbor base in Hawaii.;   The apology, if adopted, would be afirst for Japan's parliament, although during the past year various governmentofficials and Emperor Akihito have offered expressions of regret for sufferingcaused by the war.;   Bush, in an interview taped last week for broadcastSunday on ABC's &quot;This Week with David Brinkley,&quot; said it would be &quot;rankrevisionism&quot; for anyone to expect a U.S. apology.;   &quot;Not from this president.I was fighting over there. I had my orders to go back there when the warended,&quot; said Bush, who as a World War II Navy pilot was shot down in thePacific by the Japanese.;   He said that &quot;American lives were saved&quot; byPresident Truman's decision to drop the bombs, and added: &quot;Do we mourn theloss of innocent civilians? Yes. Can I empathize with a family whose child wasvictimized by those attacks? Absolutely. But I can also empathize with myroommate's mother, my roommate having been killed in action.&quot;;   According toKyodo's reports, the measure under consideration in Tokyo also would expressappreciation for the help that a defeated Japan received in recovering fromwartime devastation and express its intention to remain peaceful.;   On theABC program, Japanese Foreign Ministry spokesman Taizo Watanabe confirmed theparliament's consideration of the measure, and said Japan was not expecting areciprocal apology for the Hiroshima and Nagasaki bombings.;   &quot;That is aseparate matter,&quot; he explained. &quot;The Pearl Harbor attack memory is somethingwhich hangs over the minds of many people, and many people feel that we shoulddo something about it, to reflect on what we have done in the past and what weshould do in the future with this memory deep in our mind.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Tokyo  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911202  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  December  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  423  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday, December 2, 199100337041,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENGFRONT  </LANGUAGE></DOC>